              <!--[BEFORE-ARTICLE]--><span class="marker before-article"></span><section data-level="1" id="ref1"><!--[PREMOD1]--><span class="marker PREMOD1 mod-inline"></span><p class="topic-paragraph"><strong><span id="ref1027729"></span>meteorology</strong>,  Scientific study of atmospheric phenomena, particularly of the <a href="https://www.britannica.com/science/troposphere" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">troposphere</a> and lower <a href="https://www.britannica.com/science/stratosphere" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">stratosphere</a>. Meteorology entails the <a class="md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off eb" data-term="systematic" href="https://www.britannica.com/dictionary/systematic" data-type="EB">systematic</a> study of <a href="https://www.britannica.com/science/weather" class="md-crosslink autoxref " data-show-preview="true">weather</a> and its causes, and provides the basis for <a href="https://www.britannica.com/science/weather-forecasting" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">weather forecasting</a>. <em>See also</em> <a href="https://www.britannica.com/science/climatology" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">climatology</a>.</p><!--[MOD1]--><span class="marker MOD1 mod-inline"></span></section>


